bug.short_desc: [null][compiler]NPE in EJC for erroneous null annotations

long_desc.thetext:
Thanks for the report, I can reproduce.
We see a conflict, because the default makes it
List<@Nullable ? extends @NonNull Integer> list;
We bail out while trying to access the annotation before Integer (which we can't find because it's implicit).
OTOH, the @Nullable annotation on the wildcard should actually override the (implicit) annotation on the bound => no error to be reported.
I have a fix under test...

(In reply to Holger Klene from comment #3) > Wow you are fast!
:)
> BTW: List<@Nullable ? super Integer> listX; triggers the same error.
not any longer.
> (In reply to Stephan Herrmann from comment #1) > > List<@Nullable ? extends @NonNull Integer> list; > > Erm what about: > "This implies that @NonNull Cn is a subtype of @Nullable Cn" > http://help.eclipse.org/luna/index.jsp?topic=%2Forg.eclipse.jdt.doc. > user%2Ftasks%2Ftask-using_null_type_annotations.htm > > List<@NonNull ? extends @Nullable Integer> listE; > List<@Nullable ? super @NonNull Integer> listS; > > are actually OK?!?
Mh, technically you're right, we could try to admit such types, but they are not meaningful, the following types are exactly equivalent and less confusing:
List<@NonNull ? extends Integer> listE; List<@Nullable ? super Integer> listS;

I'll probably propose this for backporting to 4.4.1:
We have an NPE caused by implementing wrong semantics.
Fix in itself is simple, BUT depends on a change in the bug 438458 cluster of bugs.
I'll try to make up my mind about that cluster of bugs first ...
